Australia strongly opposes Japan's plans to expand whaling in Antarctic waters, aiming to establish a South Pacific whale sanctuary.
Attorney General Philip Ruddock stated that boarding Japanese ships could lead to piracy accusations due to Antarctic Treaty obligations.
Environment Minister Ian Campbell warned of potential damage to Japan's reputation if humpback whale hunting continues.
Despite diplomatic efforts, Japan persists in seeking IWC approval to increase whale catches, including endangered species.
Australia's Prime Minister John Howard criticized Japan's decision, opting for diplomatic persuasion over interception of whaling boats.
Animal rights groups face legal hurdles in stopping Japanese whaling, prompting calls for international action to prevent further slaughter of whales.
